EQUINE HERPES - USA (KENTUCKY)
*******************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org/>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 18 May 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Blood Horse, 18 May 2005 [edited]
<http://news.bloodhorse.com/viewstory.asp?id=28173>

The Blood-Horse has learned that 3 barns at Churchill Downs have been put
under quarantine because of a possible outbreak of an equine respiratory
virus. Rusty Ford of the Kentucky State Veterinarian's Office confirmed
Tuesday [17 May 2005] night an "indication" of equine herpesvirus as the
reason for the quarantine and said he was awaiting test results Wednesday
morning that could confirm the presence of the virus.
Ford did not say which trainers were affected or whether any of the barns
under quarantine contained horses scheduled to ship to Pimlico racecourse
in Baltimore, Maryland for Saturday's [21 May 2005] Preakness or other
stakes run there this weekend. 3 planeloads of horses were scheduled to
leave Louisville, Kentucky on Wednesday morning.
Among those set to leave is Kentucky Derby winner Giacomo. Ford also did
not say whether the presence of equine herpesvirus in horses at barns under
quarantine would affect shipping to Maryland of horses from other barns
stabled at Churchill Downs.
According to veterinarian Nancy S. Loving, writing in the June 2005 issue
of The Horse magazine, equine herpesvirus is classified into 5 different
strains. EHV-1 and EHV-4 are the strains associated with viral respiratory
disease. EHV-1 is the most prevalent concern in horse populations, not only
because its respiratory disease is more virulent than that caused by EHV-4,
but also because it can lead to viral abortion in mares or neurologic disease.
Fever and an upper respiratory infection are the most common signs of
EHV-1. Infected horses may show signs of lethargy, poor appetite, nasal
discharge, and a cough. An infected horse can spread the virus up to 35
feet, with a cough or snort. The virus is short-lived and susceptible to
disinfectants.
Detection of EHV-1 in 3 horses at Turfway Park in March 2003, just days
before that track's major event, the Lane's End Stakes, did not disrupt the
race, though track officials took several precautionary steps to ensure the
health of the horses at the Northern Kentucky track.
The Turfway outbreak occurred within one barn, which was put under
quarantine for 21 days. Horses shipped in to the track during that period
were housed only in the receiving barn or stakes barn, and all stalls in
those barns were stripped and thoroughly sanitized.
In a separate incident that same month [March 2003], 5 horses at Penn
National racecourse in Pennsylvania also tested positive for EHV-1. That
outbreak led officials at Philadelphia Park and at racetracks in West
Virginia to impose a temporary ban on shipping horses to and from Penn
National.
2 of the 5 horses died as a result of EHV-1. In January and February of
2003, an outbreak of EHV-1 at the University of Findlay in Ohio led to the
death of 12 horses.
