[2]
Date: 18 May 2005
From: Margie Loeser <mll@morganandpottinger.com>
Source: Courier Journal, 18 May 2005 [edited]
<http://www.%20courier-journal.com/>

2 horses put down after suspected equine herpes outbreak
-----------------------------------------------
2 horses stabled at Churchill Downs have been put down after they showed
signs of equine herpes, a highly contagious virus that affects horses'
respiratory and nervous systems, state equine agriculture officials said
Wednesday [18 May 2005].
The 2 horses euthanized in the past week have not been identified, but 3
barns with about 100 horses have been quarantined, and several other horses
have shown mild symptoms of the disease, Bob Stout, Kentucky state
veterinarian told horsemen Wednesday morning at a meeting at the track.
None of the horses being shipped from Churchill to Pimlico Race Course in
Baltimore to run in Saturday's [21 May 2005] Preakness Stakes have been
affected by the disease, said Joe De Francis, president of the Maryland
Jockey Club.
4 trainers -- Ronny Werner, Steve Asmussen, Paul McGee and Bill Cesare --
stable horses at the 3 quarantined barns, the trainers and Churchill Downs
said. None of the 4 trainers have horses entered in the Preakness.
The disease is highly contagious among horses and can be spread through
sneezing and coughing up to 35 feet away, Churchill said. Equine herpes was
1st suspected about a week ago in a horse that shipped to Churchill in mid
April 2005. The horse is believed to have come from a Florida sale, said
Rusty Ford, equine programs manager in the state veterinarian's office.
[Byline: Marcus Green]
--
Margie Loeser
<mll@morganandpottinger.com>
[Equine Herpesvirus is also known as Rhinopneumonitis and is a viral
disease caused by a herpesvirus. It may present as a severe respiratory
infection, but it may also cause a neurological disease, or abortion in
pregnant mares. There is a vaccine for it. The immunity inferred from the
disease or the vaccine are relatively short. Horses on the show or racing
circuit are often vaccinated every 6 months.
The fact that the horses running in the Preakness Race on Saturday are
apparently already shipped is good news and will help ease fears at Pimlico
Race Course. It does not, however, lessen the severity of the disease or
the tragedy. - Mod.TG]
